search.slidetext: here’s what you’ll do today create a git repository to organize all your project assets create a branch where you can safely make edits without breaking anything commit, or save, your changes to a repo branch open a pull request, to propose that your branch be combined with another merge two different branches together if you want or need more information, look out for key ideas: click these to learn more.
what’s git? create a new repository
what’s a repository? click here to create this repo!
what’s a branch? click to edit your readme!
what’s a commit? click the pull requests tab
what’s a pull request? make a new pull request
congratulations!! you’re almost done. take a moment to review the key ideas or — if you’re really confident — go straight to the knowledge assessment

git is a version control tool that helps all kinds of teams collaborate. github is a popular platform for hosting projects built with git. you can think of version control as kind of an advanced google docs, but instead of multiple people editing one document, each editor can create and work on their own version independently. then, when they’re done, they add their changes back into a master version. if you’re working on a solo project, you can use git as an advanced “save as” to experiment with different ideas in different places. return to welcome to github what’s git?

a repository is usually used to organize a single project. repositories can contain folders and files, images, videos, spreadsheets, and data sets – anything your project needs. we recommend including a readme, or a file with information about your project. github makes it easy to add one at the same time you create your new repository. your hello-world repository can be a place where you store ideas, resources, or even share and discuss things with others. return to create a repository what’s a repository?

branching is the way to work on different versions of a repository. by default, your repository has one branch named master which is the definitive branch. don’t edit that! we use branches to experiment and make edits before committing them to master. return to create a branch what’s a branch?

on github, saved changes are called commits. each commit has an associated commit message, which is a description explaining why a particular change was made. commit messages capture the history of your changes, so other contributors (and future-you!) can understand what you’ve done and why. return to make a commit what’s a commit?

open a pull request to propose that changes you made to your branch should be merged into another branch of a repository. pull requests show diffs, or differences, of the content from both branches. anything you added is highlighted in green, and deletions are highlighted in red. you can use @mentions to ask human collaborators to review your code, and you can use pull requests and merges for your own solo projects. return to open a pull request what’s a pull request?

merging is how you combine independent git branches into a single branch. usually, a person reviews various incoming pull requests, checks them for correctness and conflicts, and either approves or rejects them. some very smart software programs can also be entrusted to merge pull requests! return to merge your pull request what’s a merge?
